<paragraph blockId="13.[189,802,309,498]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
It was described from Tenerife. The lectotype shows strong differences in morphometry, mesosomal shape and sculpture to any member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[575,696,375,399]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidula">
<emphasis box="[575,696,375,399]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. pallidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex. The description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson, E. O." bookContentInfo="794 pp." box="[395,549,408,432]" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University Press, Cambridge &amp; London" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Wilson, E. O. (2003): Pheidole in the New World - a dominant and hyperdiverse ant genus. - Harvard University Press, Cambridge &amp; London: 794 pp." title="Pheidole in the New World - a dominant and hyperdiverse ant genus" type="book" year="2003">Wilson (2003)</bibRefCitation>
was not based on type material but is fully consistent with the characters of the lectotype.
</paragraph>
